      <title>Heartworm</title>
      <author> eepygirl </author>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/1322596/heartworm/</link>
      <comments>https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1322596-heartworm/chapter/1322611/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">8832fe9bd1cc66bf4825209f0a59bd16bfaf4f39</guid>
      <pubDate>Sun, 08 Dec 2024 17:13:59 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Xavier Sylberith was an enthusiastic student of a magical academy before being caught up in a ritual resulting in his untimely death. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Death, it seems, does not stick so easily when you've become a Deathless.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Alive once more, Xavier must grapple with his new nature, regenerating injuries nearly as fast as they come as he is thrust into a much larger plot than he could ever have imagined. Not to mention the Deathless he merged with fights for control of his body. Accompanied by two women known for hunting Deathless, the stakes have never been higher to maintain control.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;With progressing changes to his body from merging with a demon, Xavier will have to confront repressed feelings about his own gender, and come to terms with his new identity, in more ways than one.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1322596-heartworm/chapter/1322611/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;Chapter 1: Second Chances Do Come Cheap&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I was always told that your entire life flashes before you moments before death. Bullshit. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The only thing flashing before my eyes was the shadowy figure moving at an uncanny speed slowly piercing my chest with their claws. Be it sadistic or otherwise, the creature took its time piercing my flesh with one hand (claw?) while the other held me firmly by the throat a foot above the ground. Cries of pain were crushed in my throat, with only the pathetic remnants of screams coming out. Too many thoughts were shooting through my mind to entertain a single one. The only tangible thought my frantic mind could arrive at was- &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Make it stop&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Strangely enough, it did. In a way, at least. I had no time to react to being dropped onto the ground, feeling my legs crumple helplessly as I landed on my side. The searing pain in my chest was ever present, and I could feel blood quickly pooling and soaking my clothes where I lay on the ground. Everything sounded muffled and distant, like cotton had been stuffed in my ears and my head. Was this what it felt like to die? Not pleasant, though I suppose I never expected that to be the case.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“&lt;/span&gt;&lt;b&gt;Where is it?!”&lt;/b&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;, the harsh tone of the creature reverberated through the room, cutting through even the muffled sounds I was hearing. I lifted my head with the little energy I had left to look towards the being. It was frantically moving around the room, tossing limp bodies to the floor in search of something. The glowing orb of magic in the center of the room seemed just as frantic as the creature. What once was a purple sphere of magic was surging with black energy, shaking and quivering like it was being eaten from the inside. Perhaps bleeding out on the ground makes a man sentimental, I nearly pitied the orb as it shook with disturbing frequency, like it was crying out to-&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Make it stop&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Something I could relate to, I supposed. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;b&gt;“No, no, not yet! Where is it?”&lt;/b&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;, the creature roared out once more in search of something. My eyes landed upon a glinting amulet that rested near my head just as the creature did the same. The creature’s face lit up into a smile and moved towards the amulet. Something stirred inside of me fueled by spite or desperation as I reached out for the amulet with my arm. I had little to no energy left, making the somewhat simple action feel like I was pulling my arm through molasses. The sick smile on the creature's face twisted into that of hatred. No. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Fear&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;? Not that it mattered much to a dying man.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;“NO! IGNORANT HUMAN”&lt;/b&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;, The creature let out an ear-splitting cry as it dived for the amulet. My hands wrapped around the amulet first, with the creature’s claws wrapping around my hand soon after. The violent orb of magic had completely turned black at this point, shrinking into itself before letting out a brilliant burst of magic. I felt my hand crushed by the creature as the wave of magic washed over the both of us. It burned, &lt;/span&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;Gods&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; did it burn. It hurt more than I could possibly put into words, I needed it to stop. I NEEDED IT TO STOP JUST-&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Make it stop&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;It did.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;h1 style="text-align:center"&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;* * * * *&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h1&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Xavier?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;It was a soft voice; one I knew all too well. “Vyra? Where are you?”. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;No answer. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Where am I?”. All I could see around me was pure, unbridled darkness. It didn’t feel as though my feet were touching anything, yet no pull of gravity made me feel as though I was falling. Was this the afterlife? A dream? If this truly was the afterlife, what a mighty fine disappointment it was. A short life filled with unrequited feelings and unmet dreams culminating in a one-way ticket to floating in a dark void. A funny joke, if it wasn’t about myself.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I should have stayed home. With a weekend free from my classes, I had every right to find something to entertain myself with. But for some fucking reason I went back to the castle. Vyra had always mocked me for being a teacher’s pet, and though I would never admit it, she was right. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;A predilection for affirmations made me the perfect vessel for being a teacher’s pet. I had been thoroughly studious my entire education, but it only got more fervorous the older I got. As soon as magic had been discussed in my classes, I was obsessed. I figured if I didn’t have any natural affinity like some did, I would need to work extra hard to make up for it. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Had that resulted in any ability to perform magic? No… maybe I’m just foolish, but it still hasn't deterred me away from my passion for the magical arts. The very same reason I had returned to the castle to speak to one of my professors. When he wasn’t in his classroom, I should have just taken that as a sign. When I found his not-so-secret passageway in the classroom, I should have taken that as a sign. When I walked for what felt like a mile to encounter a strange ritual, I should have taken that as a sign. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Curiosity killed the cat? No, stupidity killed this cat. Now I’m floating in what I can only assume is the afterlife.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;My thoughts were interrupted by a strange sensation. The already dark void seemed to be getting darker? How was that possible? The emptiness surrounding me seemed to grow thicker, heavier, pressing into my body on all sides provoking an uncomfortable claustrophobia. A distant sound grew steadily louder. What started as a buzz became a scream. Turning my head to the direction of the sound resulted in a horrifying sight. The same monstrous creature from moments before was charging towards me with hate in their eyes, making my stomach turn and the hair all over my body to stand on edge. You couldn’t die in the afterlife, right?! Right?! All too quickly, the creature raced towards me, a menacing claw raised up to stab through me once more. I closed my eyes and braced for the pain to come.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;…and waited.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;My eyes opened to an entirely different sight. Before me was a cold stone doorway. Looking up revealed I was in what looked to be a… church? I laid atop an altar; pews evenly spaced all the way to the back wall of the building. I was wet. No, the altar was wet. Looking up towards the sky revealed the answer to my confused mind. I was being drenched by rain, and this church lacked a ceiling. As I crawled off the altar and onto the floor, I noticed the lack of a ceiling was not of choice, but instead time. The entire church was dilapidated and forgotten. The stone structure had been whittled away through the steady march of time, and though I would not claim to be an expert in dating things, I could easily tell this building had not seen care for centuries.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;My attention was pulled towards my feet when I stepped in a pool of rainwater collecting in a broken section of the floor. “W-what?” I uttered a shaky breath as I stared down at my foot. My foot was covered by some sort of shadow. Despite stepping ankle deep in the water, my foot felt completely dry, protected by a translucent shadow that traveled up my legs, stopping just above my knees. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Panic quickly ensued, immediate instinct telling me to get it off. I fell backwards, pulling up my right legs and attempting to peel off whatever was stuck to my leg, only to notice a similar substance covering my arms up to my elbows. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“No, no! Get off!! S-Shit!”. Minutes passed of pure fear until I eventually came to the conclusion that, try as I might, whatever the substance is was not coming off. I began to cry. Everything was too much. I should be dead, long gone, yet here I was in some sort of church with shadows clinging to my body. I shouldn’t be alive! None of this should be happening! Why didn’t it just stop when the magic orb burned me away?! I just needed it to stop, please just-&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Make it stop.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I crawled towards the collected water, staring fearfully into my reflection. The same short black hair that I always had was still there, though it almost looked longer? My eyes, shit, my eyes were a deep red, no longer the soft green that they had always been. They looked furious, like just by staring at myself I was in some sort of danger. Most notably, I saw a dark tattoo stretched across my neckline. The markings were obviously deliberate, looking almost like some sort of language that I had never seen in my life. The tattoo looked alive, like an inky cloudiness was swirling across my front. It was too much, I started to cry. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Senses completely overloaded, and heart throbbing painfully in my chest, I felt a darkness creeping into the sides of my vision. With one last pained cry ripping through my throat, I felt my grip on my consciousness fade, and my vision went black.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;h1 style="text-align:center"&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;* * * * *&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h1&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Awake. Alive? I feel different. Taking a moment to glance across my own form, I know something is wrong. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;This isn’t me. &lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;No, it can’t be. This is the &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;h u m a n&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; body. The ignorant sack of meat who ruined everything, who ruined the ritual. Wait.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;The ritual.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;That miserable thing ruined the ritual! How is he still alive?! How am I? &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;There is a musty scent that sits in the air. Having presumably rained for some time, this destroyed church is soaked in the rain. It’s old architecture holding in the rain through cracks and divots created through attrition. The stone tells a story of decay and old tales. Clearly no one has been here in some time, a thought that brings some joy. I’m no friend to the churches, and they are no friend of mine. Out of pure curiosity, I searched the church for some sigil or emblem that would tell me which God this church was constructed for. Not that it would help, but it would bring a smile to my face to know which of the Gods was being so neglected. Behind the altar a molded tapestry sat sopping wet in a puddle of rainwater. I clawed at the edge of the tapestry to lift it without touching the rotted material, thankfully it was enough to spot a certain emblem belonging to none other than-&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;That’s no God. I let the tapestry fall back into the pooling water as I backed up into the altar behind me. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;Baehevar.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; The Fiend of the Dead. Never in my many years of life have I seen any worship to &lt;strong&gt;Baehevar&lt;/strong&gt;, for all I knew he was completely forgotten. Where had I found myself? Where did this Godsforsaken human put me?!&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Hello? I heard a scream, are you okay?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;A gruff voice traveled through what was left of this dilapidated blasphemous church. Instinctively I ducked behind the altar, pressing myself low to the ground with a flexibility that was far beyond that of a human. Frustratingly, this form seemed to lack the full extent of flexibility I was used to. Probably that &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;f i l t h y&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; human’s form holding me back. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Is someone there? Don’t be afraid, I’m a clergyman from Tiere. Are you hurt?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Clergy. Maybe my luck wasn’t as bad as I thought. I was so &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;h u n g r y&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;. This would make for the most excellent meal. With a grin stretching to each side of my face, I prepared to speak.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“H-help me. Please!”. The voice that exited my throat perplexed me. It felt like some combination of my own voice, distinctly feminine and sultry, and the harsh tone of the man whose body I found myself in. I hated it. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The clergyman moved towards the altar, rushing over with very little care for his own safety. Unfortunate. When he got close enough, I leapt onto the stone altar, shadowy claws sinking into the damp stone. The sickening crack paired with the horrifying visage in front of the clergyman caused him to stop in his tracks. With how paralyzed he looked, I thought for a moment that he might’ve made a good mime. Pity he chose the path he did. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I felt my joints pop into place, like my (his?) body was actively shifting. A quick glance down revealed exactly that. What could have been perceived as a masculine form was molding into a much more sleek and feminine form, one that I was very familiar with. Down to the miniscule touches, I seemed to be capable of morphing this ugly form into a close approximation of the &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;Deathless&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; woman that I was. The disgusting display of bones cracking and reshaping, sinew tearing and reattaching in front of his eyes made the clergyman’s eyes widen. Every sense in his body told him to move, but not a single muscle reacted to his commands. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;With an elusive speed I dismounted the altar onto the porous stone in front of the old man. Rising to meet him face to face, I spread my lips, razor sharp fangs reflecting his fearful gaze. His &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;f e a r&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; was delectable, the sweetest treat a girl could hope for given my circumstances. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Enough playing with my food. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;h1 style="text-align:center"&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;* * * * *&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h1&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;My eyes flitted open, the bright light of the sun beaming directly into my irises. Gods I was sore, every extremity resonated with a cutting pain that made me feel like I had run for miles the previous day. Pushing aside the soreness, I got myself onto my two feet to assess my situation.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Good news, I no longer had shadows coating my legs and arms.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Bad news, I was covered in blood.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Fuck!”. I threw a hand over my mouth to stop from gagging at the grisly sight of an old man in front of me. Unfortunately, the hand over my mouth was slick with blood, forcing out a retch as I attempted to keep whatever might have been in my stomach down. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;An old man with a gaping cavity where his heart should be lay squarely in the center of the church. It was overwhelming to the senses. The thick scent of death was just as nauseating as the gore painting the aisle. I couldn’t get away from it, blood stained most of my body. It was only now I realized I was wearing what could only generously be referred to as ‘clothing’. I had been wrapped up in some sort of fabric. It tightly hugged my chest, down to my thighs, like I had been mummified before someone left on a lunch break and never returned. The fabric itself should have been white, but with the viscera covering me, it was more of a ‘suggestion’ of white.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The entire scene was horrifying, but even more so were the implications. Did I do this? I have no memory indicating that I did, but I couldn’t deny what lay in front of me. My arms were stained a dark red, like I had been attempting to excavate the man’s entire body with just my fingers. A disgusting thought, made infinitely worse when I felt something stuck in my teeth. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;No.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Surely it wasn’t… &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I closed my eyes, tears slowly collecting in the corners of my eyes as I reached a hand into my mouth to pull out whatever was stuck in my mouth. With minor difficulty I managed to pull it out only to have to stare hopelessly at what looked to be some sort of organ. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Fuck.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;It had to be a nightmare. This couldn’t get any worse. In only a day I had died, come back, and become something other than human. A poor clergyman lay lifelessly beneath me. I would be stupid to think he died for any reason other than myself. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“W-why..?”. I croaked out through tears. Even my voice sounded wrong. My usual deep voice sounded lighter, still masculine, but an octave above what it used to be. It sounded harsh as well, like there were bristles in my throat slicing into my words. What was I? What was happening to me?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Voices. Distant voices that only seemed to get closer as I stood frozen over my nightmarish canvas. People were coming. I looked down to the body that lay in front of me, and the blood that had covered my body and my soul.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Fuck.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;div class="wi_authornotes"&gt; &lt;div&gt; &lt;div class="p-avatar-wrap"&gt;&lt;a class="avatar has-link" href="/profile/184214/eepygirl/"&gt;&lt;img id="acc_ava_change profile" alt="" src="https://cdn.scribblehub.com/avatar/s/46/ava_184214_1732782556.jpg"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span class="an_username"&gt;&lt;a href="/profile/184214/eepygirl/"&gt;eepygirl&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div style="clear: both;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="wi_authornotes_body"&gt;  Hello! I hope you enjoyed the first chapter! This is my first story I've written, so I'm sure there are plenty of mistakes that I'm going to make along this journey, but that's okay! It's going to be a fun learning experience for me, and hopefully an enjoyable read for you. I have a lot of wonderful plans for this story already that I can't wait to share :3&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I also loooooove feedback! So if you've got the time, leave a comment, tell me what you think, and tune in for the next chapter!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
