    <item>
      <title>Somewhere In The Stars</title>
      <author> Adra_Collins </author>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/1321539/somewhere-in-the-stars/</link>
      <comments>https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1321539-somewhere-in-the-stars/chapter/1321546/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">0276ecfc755b8eb02302a9f7fd108f26194bf32d</guid>
      <pubDate>Wed, 27 Nov 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Marc lives on a terraformed planetoid designated as Colony 7 where he's spent the past 19 years of his living an unsatisfying life in the galactic equivalent of a Mining Town.  One day, things get weird, and when his best friend flakes on him for unknown reasons he acts on a curious impulse simply out of anger. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;His actions trigger a chain of events that will effect the rest the rest of his life and everyone connected to it.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1321539-somewhere-in-the-stars/chapter/1321546/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;7 days ago&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;I watched as the ships roared by overhead, the scale of their whale-like massiveness casting a silhouette of night over everything below.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Imperium was here. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Days ago something was found here on Colony 7. Nobody dared to talk about it. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In the time since &lt;i&gt;it&lt;/i&gt; was found, nature had gone quiet. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;and no one dared venture back into the mines. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;What It was…it had changed something long before the ship had ever come into the system. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;in a single cycle of the moon The Imperials had spun everything upside down..&lt;i&gt;looking.&lt;/i&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:center"&gt;&lt;b&gt;Chapter 1&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:center"&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:center"&gt;&lt;i&gt;7 days ago. &lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I hate it here. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Everyone kind of hates Colony 7 but I like to think I hate it in an entirely unique way. Something about the way it’s shaped my outsides and rotted my insides with its unique odors and culture. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Which I suppose isn’t unique, but it’s &lt;i&gt;my&lt;/i&gt; hatred. And that has to count for something. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A mining colony pulling up ore, to burn for…I don’t know. I just work here. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;We mine Anduminium. We ship it off to the Imperium back home. We get sent rations in return. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;About five hundred or so people exist on the planetoid, the mining is the only thing we have to do after the automation and the terraforming had ensured we’ll be able to live here. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Core Worlds tech thrives on the Anduminium. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Some of the researchers from before I was alive argue that we “healed the planet before figuring out whether it was broken” but the fact that it was a source of what the Imperium needed superseded that entirely. What was it before? Doesn’t matter. Core Worlds need Anduminium. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And the needs of Imperium, matter first and foremost. We work to make sure it is strong, so it can make sure we are safe.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Safe from what?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I just work here. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Marc, get your ass over here and bring the picks!” the foreman yells across the chasm. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Right. Work. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I push all my body weight directly into the equipment cart, the gravity dampening lifts doing their own share of the work as every worker who crosses me takes their pick for the upcoming shifts worth of mining. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I get the cart parked, here it will sit as a refuel dock and partially a bench and desk for the foreman. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Underneath my feet is cold hard rock that's been worn down by high pressure water that gives the mine a mildewed smell, an ‘Alive’ smell is what I called it when I was a kid. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I take my pick. and press the hard metal against where the vein is leading us. Just one of at least a hundred of us today. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I pull the trigger, lean all the way into the thing, bracing my weight into the chassis of the pick and the rotor goes to work vibrating the pick and shaking me all the way into my bones. Lose bits of debris tumble to the ground, slowly I break away more and more revealing the shining white of the Anduminium ore inside. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;This is life in Colony 7: tedious, repetitive, but my dad would call it “honest work” Not that the foreman would call it anything else. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I’ve been working since I hit sixteen core years of age, my arms adapted well to all this work. I’m tall, full of angles.  hair kept hemmed in with lots of shaving. A shadow of stubble over my jawline. I wish I could have it longer, but the risk of work accidents means just razoring every last inch is probably better. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;three years of that. Some of the old hats all talk about the way the mine slowly eats you, physically and emotionally. And I can’t help but wonder how soon that sets in. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Cause honestly, I think I felt it the moment I hit seventeen. I am nineteen now. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;How is this my whole life? &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The pick vibrates and I feel it again in the bones, in the hands. The sensory experience will linger for about a minute. I’ve counted how long it sticks before I lose track of it. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Mine is as old as I’ve been working at it. It was a cave once. Or so I’m told. It’s the active mining site. We’ll work it until it’s dry, move to the next. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;They say that’s what the mines do to us in turn. Those old hats I mentioned earlier. We break it down, and it breaks us down. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It sucks. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Day in. And day out. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;As I braced myself into the pick, watching chunks of glowing detritus that would be sorted and filed away to be shipped back to The Core Worlds, I awaited the lunch bell. One hour lunch. I’d go to Macros and eat a simple lunch, then I’d come back. Work another 5 hours. Then I’d go home. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Today was different. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Not necessarily because I wanted it to be, though I did. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But because, if it exists, fate had something planned for me. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;4 hours into my shift there was a disturbance that a few people had started crowding around. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;An entire section of the original cave system had been uncovered after a fork in the strip mine we’d slowly been breaking down. That wasn’t uncommon as the caves were, well….cavernous. Big breathing things that carved themselves into the planet. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Even the Team Lead was caught up in the sight of The Peculiarity. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;This section was different. When I got there everyone was feeling up the stone. Smooth, The stone wall we had all gathered up towards was different enough that everyone close enough knew well that something was off. The stone “oozed” like it had dripped down from the ceiling in huge sheets, drying in this shape.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;When I touched it. Something resonated. I pushed and the stone felt like it could crumple like paper somehow. I don't know why, but I became fixated on the perceived fragility. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Before any further investigation could my da- The Foreman showed up. Telling everyone to spread out. He investigated it. And wrote it off.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Must have been a dead volcano or something, a stray elemental got in here and melted it for some eggs.” a litany of excuses to usher us back to our jobs. Time wasted was lost anduminium and pay. Things that would give the accountant a headache to work on. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And so we left. Back to the laborious efforts of daily work. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:center"&gt;*3*&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Lunch came. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Tritt was a quick guy with an assortment of floating drones that quickly slotted plates onto counter tops of the food stall. Bowls of street corn, and plates of hot fries, whirled around him, somewhere on the opposite end of the area his mother dutifully cooked and chorused in the creole language of Nueva derived from certain asian communities under the republic of unified mexico&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Sitting before me was a plate of exactly those two things, with an additional browny, and a lemon-lime soda. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I ate slower than usual and Tritt took notice of it. “What's on the mind, Marc?” he inquired, "you're usually a lot more quick with the food. It’s not underwhelming is it?” &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Oh… nah, it’s good. I’m just-” I dragged off thinking, “Something happened at work and it’s eatin’ me a bit.” &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Someone get chewed up in the sorter?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I remembered the gruesome memory best not lingered upon. “No..weird stone wall. Dads said not to mine into it cause it might be elemental eggs.” &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“And you think it’s something else?” Tritt smirked his odd smile he used whenever he knew he was reading my thoughts. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Funny… but yeah. Don't know why… but, I might…” &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Yelling at him from across the stall one of the other patrons took Tritt's attention and he had to rush off with a hurried excuse to handle it. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I spent the rest of the lunch break quietly contemplating the flavors alongside just what I Was thinking of doing when the shift had ended. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The crowds in the main thoroughfare of the colony was dense with a variety of individuals. Mostly human, but tall and lanky folks with grey skin and personal gravity rigs from the moons of Mars strolled by. Spidery 8 legged humanoids that moved hastily, delivering packages who hailed from Aeon-V.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And then me. Human. Born on colony 7. Will die on Colony 7, sentenced to death before I was even alive. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;So obviously, I thought something in that barred off restricted section would mean &lt;i&gt;something&lt;/i&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And I didn’t know how right I was. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:center"&gt;*2*&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The day went by with little issue after I got back from lunch. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;We worked around the “Melt” as the foreman called it. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Someone got curious though. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Not by a lot. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But I can tell someone had used their pick on the layer. There was a hole. Just big enough to look through with the eye. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I ignored it as best I could.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The sounds, heavy machinery. Occasionally people would find a working song rhythm ,most of it was drowned out by the breaking and vibration of rock. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Hanging&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Banging&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Working till we die. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Empty &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Tunnels &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Moving Metal til caves cry.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The music faded out as I lost track of things. The Melt. I couldn’t ignore it. But I worked. Distractedly.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Shift ended. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The moment I got off shift I’d have two hours before sundown and dinner would be at home. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Outside the active mine was rows and rows of carts hawking chincy wares and foods, people barking all sorts of promised goods and services; Roast Beef sandwiches that taste just like the core worlds, toy trains that made musical noises as they buggied along their miniature railways, an endless assortment of plastic swords and glowing necklaces. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A smell of food and booze was all about the stone floor of the tunnels that lead back to the surface. Some of the old bled mines had homes built into the sides and even some up in the very high ceilings, in spite of the risk. Dripping laundry, house cooked meals and the like.  Once the mines “died” they became full of new life in the form of inhabitants. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There was a foolhardy belief that as a mining colony the miners had a lot of spare money, they risked their lives and dug for valuable resources so it must stand to reason we get paid a good compensation. My dad does. I Don’t. The Stands mean nothing to me. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It was always an anomaly to me that Colony 7 was nothing important. A mining colony, yet the population was dense. The History explained that it was just a three hundred man mining expedition, on the terraformed planetoid. Three hundred men and their families. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; seven generations later and I’d lost track of the last census numbers. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Anduminium never stopped. So the “expedition” never ended. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Sooner or later I was born into it. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Sooner or later we were all born into it. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;So why the hell would anyone want to voluntarily be near it? Especially when there is so little to be gained from it? &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The streets moved and flowed like river water, a consistent tide that rolled and moved you. I was propped against a vending machine, the warmth of its motor inside the casing provided a sturdy shoulder to lean on as I stared on into the mass of people. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I had my Vapo-Stick. Pinched between my index, ring, and thumb. I inhaled the cloud of banana flavoring. Or what could be simulated artificially of it. Bananas were grown off in the dyson spheres,  back in the core, hyper environmentally controlled greenhouses orbiting suns. Colony 7 was always supposed to have some sort of promised “shipments” of bananas. But that's been about the same kind of promise as getting a micro fleet of drill-walkers. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Bananas in Colony 7. A mighty fine joke if there ever was one. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I exhaled the taste into the air above my head, the custardy yellow mist hanging above me, dissipating and being pulled away into an air vent, the vending machine sat outside a communal shower house. Inside were more vending machines for soaps, loofahs, condoms, shower caps, and other things. &lt;br /&gt;The Air Vent… I assumed it went up to the surface part of the colony. Funneling my vapor smoke, shower steam, and who knows what other collection of smells and chemicals from the mine up into the artificially created atmosphere.  &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Tritt was supposed to meet me here. He was supposed to meet me here an hour ago….&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I inhaled from the stick again. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He flaked. Of course Tritt Flaked. In the past few months I couldn't catch him outside his work. And everytime now the few times we got to see one another he’d have to immediately leave after a quick smoke. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Inside me I soured at the thought that our friendship was starting to wither and die. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;‘The Mine slowly eats you’ The notion echoed in my head. Of course. Of course it would. What else would it do, What else could I blame? Who could I blame, it was irrational to try and blame anyone. Tritt and I were being pulled in separate directions and this disgusting Colony was going to eat everything I valued and I &lt;i&gt;hated&lt;/i&gt; it. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I scowled. My boots stomped over the worn out stone. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Every now and again I’d bump past someone, muttering an ‘excuse me' or a ‘pardon me,’ and a ‘sorry-about-that.’&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The world was narrowing as waded through, eventually back in the mine. The smell of the wet, “living” stone surrounding me as I got deeper, the echoing drip&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Drip&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Drip&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Drip of water from somewhere inside the cave, the sound having an almost Conversive rhythm. The Mine seemed to ask in a very earnest way. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;What&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Are you&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Doing?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Scratching an itch. That's what I’m doing. You’ve felt the curiosity. The wiggling wonder that every one inside of you had. Why should you hold your secrets? You're a mine. If I don't have that privilege, then neither do you. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Helmet, ventilator mask, Pick. I hefted the gear with practiced precision, placing the tapered metal directly into the narrowest part of that hole someone had gouged into The Melt. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I had at least one better thing I could be doing right now. I could be at home. I could be chasing down Tritt.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;No. I was going in. I was taking some degree of control. Maybe dad would be pissed off at me, I didn’t know. And I didn't care. Not at the moment. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The solo vibrations of the pick was like an extension of the screams of rage I was feeling in my gut right now as I slowly, precisely. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Broke&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Cracked. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And shape&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A hole into The Melt. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;No more secrets. I panted from the vibrations, letting out a breath I hadn’t realized I was holding in. I had something big enough for me to duck through. Despite being porous the wall of the melt maintained itself as though it was doing its best to uphold some sort of command it had been given. The fact it never collapsed with all the vibrations from the work around it, or from being directly worked on with a pick almost made me imagine that somehow the rock would superheat again, melting the hole I’d made closed. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A brief horrifying mental image of the oozing magma wall grabbing my tools and my arms and pulling me away as a warning that even if we had mastered the mines Colony 7 would always hold some secrets. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I shook my head. No time to be suspicious now. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I ducked into the hole and into the new cavern. Its secrets are now open to me, and everyone who would come after me. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Of course, my actions would have consequences. For all of Colony 7… &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:center"&gt;*1*&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The incline of the tunnel that I’d uncovered was concerning. I half slid, half climbed down. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;No eggs. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;No sign of an elemental either. In fact if I was honest, so much of the rock formation felt like more mine. Which seemed impossible, if simply because the active mine had only revealed the Melt today.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Peculiarity. Did not like that.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The rock was too smooth. I quietly pressed forward. Considering the possibilities of an elemental being down here. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Elementals were big, what little I knew about them was simple enough…or not? They existed “parallel to time” creatures that crawled out of reality when sentient beings achieved faster than lightspeed travel. Everytime a spaceship traveled a long distance there was a chance an elemental could crack open and cause some chaos in the wake of its trail. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Elementals can’t leave after they’re “trapped here.” Whatever the hell that means. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;If there were no eggs then I could tell dad it was fine to mine down here…though the mystery now was why the hell this place looked like a mine already. Maybe we were overlapping with a strip from an earlier mine? Didn’t make sense cause there were no signs or sounds of life down here either. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I paused my thinking as I stared forward. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;… Door. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The giant door in the tunnel ahead of me was massive. Maybe 100 feet tall? I was reminded of a giant hangar door from pictures of old planes from the core worlds. I closely approached realizing the sounds of my boots on the floor changed, almost soundless the way it hit rock to the dull steps of boot on dirt to…smoothed metal. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Peculiarity grew bigger. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The symbol of a circle with a singular line breaking the northern hemisphere of the circle was emblazoned upon the door. I knew this symbol as the crest of the Imperium. Or at least some iteration of it. the one I knew was spiked with five lines; two on either side of the main one at the center of the top of it. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;To the left side of the panel there was a simple panel of buttons. A series of numbered buttons in the “universal” language. An enter key..and a flat pad I knew would likely have been a fingerprint scanner for humanoids. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I hesitated, my adventure would either end here…or…&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I pressed my index finger to the scanner…a beep rang in my ears and the door split open. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Adventure continues. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I pulled off the ventilator and breathed in the air. It wasn’t stale. More peculiarity. The air purifier was not only still working, but more so active. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I want to imagine a normal person would have turned and tried to get back. I think at any other moment I might have been that person. I don’t know if normal ever was something I liked being. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The amount of mirrored surfaces that were just transparent enough to make out technology underneath was a lot. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Mirrors made me feel like I was going to vomit. I hated my own reflection. I wasn’t pretty to look at. Even with all the ways I’d tried to make myself look “presentable” as a miner. I just didn’t have a face worth looking at, even if the person looking was myself. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Stubble of a million shaves, protruding cheek bones.  &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The lights seemed to automatically click on as I walked down the hallway, the darkness retreating as I made my way toward… &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Where was I going? &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I broke The Melt because I was angry. Now I was just confused, wandering endlessly. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A terminal appeared at a corner and I let out an “aha!” sound. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It turned on in response to my touch. I quickly tapped along the keyboard, the sound was soft, yet echoed in the empty hall. Poking around I found the most important thing. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It was a battleship. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Designation: IIBC 151413-“Onward To The Stars”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;An Imperial Battleship hidden inside of a planetoid sized mining colony. That…would be impossible. And more so..how the hell has it never been discovered by the miners. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Well I had a hunch for that. More often than not the mines move on preplanned pathways, an algorithm determining the most likely areas to determine where Anduminium deposits are. So, maybe there's something in the machines to guide us away when we get too close? &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;That still doesn’t address why it’s here. Getting it &lt;i&gt;into&lt;/i&gt; the planet would be implausible, and teleporting it &lt;i&gt;out&lt;/i&gt; would absolutely destroy a sizable chunk of the planet if not the whole damn thing. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Could Colony 7 be artificial? &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;My fingers poked at all sorts of basic things, floor plans, commissioning dates, service periods. It was listed as “fueling.” &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I felt an itch of anxiety. Could there be people here somehow? &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Biting down on my lip before inhaling deep, I stepped back from the terminal. I had to know. I just had to know. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I made my way through a series of empty spaces. Each light continued to turn on, and each light ushering a squeezing in my gut that made me worry someone would be there. Most I had on me was a simple multitool pocket knife. If by some dark miracle there was a soldier or someone else on this ship I’d be screwed. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Empty rooms were barracks, a mess hall, there was an armory but it was locked off tight, with a dna recognition pad that looked league different from what the initial docking door I’d used.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Somewhere I knew from the map there was a launch bay. While this ship wasn’t so big it would be able to house a fleet, it would have no doubt a handful of small flyers and at least a small trio of mech suits. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The one room that never responded to my presence was the bridge. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The quiet started to get to me, every little noise be it my footsteps, a door opening, or even some sort of noise the ship made from who knows how long it’s sat here felt like a beckoning for me to turn back. To leave while I could…&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But I followed along, checking terminals where they appeared to keep track of my path until eventually..&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I was outside. Outside-ish. The front exterior deck of the ship There were docking areas for small fighter ships. And tall docks for mechs. The ceiling had a wide open line going down the center and I could smell the mine again. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The line would extend just big enough for the ships and mechs to depart from. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I quietly walked along the path of the runway, Every dock was empty. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Except for one. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She had to have been at least 80 feet tall, maybe taller. Her legs reminded me of a bird. Clawed, dangerous. Long arms, one of which seemed to have an integrated blade weapon that I couldn’t make out entirely.  Her entire finish was a shining black, certain joint areas along the chassis of her body was inlaid with gold linework &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;From where I could make it out her head looked as though she were wearing a crown. And wing-like structures were folded in along her back. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Wow.” my voice echoed all over. “You are gorgeous.” I walked up closer, craning my neck upwards to look, taking more of her in.  I gently placed my hand on the smooth surface. The ‘skin’ is cold. And all I can think out loud was…&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“How long have you been hidden away down here?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I hadn’t expected an answer.  The silence of the hangar was disrupted by a loud rush as I heard the reactors inside spin up. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In a moment of panic I pulled back and stepped away cautiously. Her eyes lit up in the vibrant purple, that same life giving purple energy shimmering along lines down along her chassis that reminded me of some of the bioluminescent tattoos on core worlders who travelled through here from time to time   &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She opened up to me, a bright white shining out as the exterior of her chest telescoped inside of itself, revealing the heart inside. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Cockpit was on a rail system that folded outward as it descended down. While I was no stranger to mech technology my experience was limited to the simple mining tech we were allowed here on Colony 7. The long since broken down mining suits were small enough that all you had to do was pull yourself and wiggle your way in through a roll cage into an incredibly rudimentary control suite. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;This one was massively different though., a sphere of metal panels that reflected my face into me as it met me, and then slid open, the curving circle holding its shape as the door opened, the control panels adjusted to allow a pilot to climb in before being locked away in their newer form.  &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I stared into the empty cockpit. Mesmerized at the sight, cushioned seating, the array of levers, buttons, and switches. Flickering hypnotically. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I imagined this is how prey animals felt in the sight of predators as they were stared down. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A sense of trepidation bearing down on me as I looked into The Machine. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Despite what little I knew about the rudimentary base level A.I. the fact that it couldn’t possibly be intelligent enough to SEE me in its current state…that I could exist to it as anything more than a registered blip in motion sensing radar. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Whatever happened next, I was going to let it happen. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I held out my hand forward…and stepped forward into my fate. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Mech took a step forward as its eyes shifted red,, and from the cockpit within a series of cables snapped out like vipers, lunging to meet me. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A needle stabbed into the back of my hand, plunging into the vein. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A computerised voice suddenly echoed out of the speakers inside the cockpit.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;[Initiating Genetic Analysis. Processing.]&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I immediately snapped back to rational panic, reaching to grab at the cable, but- my eyes were blinded with a red flash of lasers that met my eyes before moving past and around my head, leaving my vision blurry and my body stunned.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There was an awareness of several flickering lights from the cockpit that enveloped my body as it did so.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;[Brainwave Scanning Initiated.]&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Cables suddenly pulled back; instinctively I held tightly to the back area of my hand to slow the bleeding. My heart hammered in my chest mimicking the rhythm of the pick axes as I stared at the cockpit, unsure of what it was doing, and too terrified to move.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;[Soul Encryption has begun.]... [Constructing A.I. Co-Pilot]…&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Voice of the computer pitch shifted far higher sounding much less like something that came from the depth of hell &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;[Processing]...&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The single word carried a weight that rang in my head ominously. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;[Processing]...&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Mech's eyes returned its original purple hued glow. The interior cockpit shined a beam of light that suddenly spread out like a spray of vapor&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Female voice spoke out. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;[Generating AI. Co-Pilot based on pilots brainwaves. Thank you for trusting in Midas.]...&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The “spray” of blue glowing light narrowed and reshaped itself. A hologram. I’d read about them being more widespread on bigger planets. Never got to interact with them before. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Based on my brain waves…so I’d be talking to myself? &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;No. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Glow suddenly took on a humanoid form, exactly my height but that's where it all ended. The woman standing opposite me had shoulder length hair, was…not naked but the body simply didn’t have any “sex parts” the shape being the “suggestion” of curves. The Skin simply…existed. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She ‘breathed in’ deeply and smiled at me. With a voice that sounded like an amalgamation of my own and my mothers she greeted me. “Hello, Sister.” &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;My fear won. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;My vision blurred and my mind went on autopilot, self defensively running. Somewhere I could make out the sounds of a “Maria, wait!” but I dare not look back. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The hangar became the interior of the battleship, which became the interior of the mine once more. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Adrenaline propelled me up the incline and out of The Melt. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Forcing myself to walk out of the mine. My breath came out in ragged breaths as my sides and lower back screamed in agony. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I wouldn’t think. The thoughts in my head were traitorous curiosity that would undoubtedly lead to the death of everything I cared about. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I got home later than I had planned. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I ate dinner in my bedroom. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I fell asleep&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;My life was never going to be the same. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;div class="wi_authornotes"&gt; &lt;div&gt; &lt;div class="p-avatar-wrap"&gt;&lt;a class="avatar has-link" href="/profile/60336/adra_collins/"&gt;&lt;img id="acc_ava_change profile" alt="" src="https://cdn.scribblehub.com/avatar/s/15/ava_60336_1626838118.jpg"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span class="an_username"&gt;&lt;a href="/profile/60336/adra_collins/"&gt;Adra_Collins&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div style="clear: both;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="wi_authornotes_body"&gt;  &lt;br /&gt;Feel Free to donate to my Ko-Fi or Patreon&lt;br /&gt;This is for me. In the time between, I got this idea sometime in september and rattled off a story idea and decided it would be best "hold onto it" until Witch's Gambit was done.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Then...shit happened and Chapter 11 felt way bigger, and then the whole book felt *bigger* and so this story is going to be a side project I intermittently prod at while working on Witch's Gambit. That story I will do my hardest to maintain a chapter once a month, but this will be a "when the next chapter is done" kind of deal. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
